No, you cannot access the control-specific states and information provided by `ngModel` without assigning it to a template reference variable with `#email="ngModel"` or a similar construct.

By default, when you use the `ngModel` directive within a form, Angular automatically creates a `FormControl` instance for that input. This instance has properties and methods that track the state of the control, such as `valid`, `dirty`, `touched`, etc. However, to access this control programmatically within your template, you must create a template reference variable.

Here's an example again to clarify:

```html
<!-- This input has ngModel, but there is no template reference variable to access its state -->
<input type="text" class="form-control" id="email" name="email" ngModel required email>

<!-- This input has ngModel, and the template reference variable, `email`, lets you access the control's state -->
<input type="text" class="form-control" id="email" name="email" ngModel required email #email="ngModel">
```

Without `#email="ngModel"`, the `FormControl` instantiated by `ngModel` is still there, and Angular still tracks its state, but you have no handle to refer to this `FormControl` directly in the template. To get access to the `FormControl` associated with the `ngModel` without a template reference variable, you would instead have to interact with it programmatically through the `NgForm` directive by querying for the control using its name:

```typescript
// Inside your component class
export class SomeComponent {
  @ViewChild('f') formDirective: NgForm;

  someMethod() {
    // Access the FormControl for the email input using its name 'email'
    const emailControl = this.formDirective.form.get('email');
    // Now you can access its state and value
    console.log(emailControl.value);
    console.log(emailControl.valid);
  }
}

// In your template
<form (ngSubmit)="onFormSubmit()" #f="ngForm">
  <!-- The input without "#email" -->
  <input type="text" class="form-control" id="email" name="email" ngModel required email>
</form>
```

To summarize, if you want to reference the form control state within the template easily, then you need a template reference variable like `#email="ngModel"`. If you're okay with accessing the control state only within the component class and not directly within the template, then you could do without the explicit template reference variable.

In Angular, `@ViewChild()` is a decorator that you can use to access a child component, directive, or a DOM element from within your component class. When you apply `@ViewChild()` to a class property, Angular populates that property with the corresponding reference.

In your case, `@ViewChild('f') signupForm!: NgForm;` is used to grab a reference to the `NgForm` directive instance associated with the template-driven form in the component's template. 'f' is the template reference variable name given to the form in the template, matching the argument you've used for `@ViewChild()`.

The `!` after `signupForm` is a TypeScript non-null assertion operator, which tells the TypeScript compiler that `signupForm` will not be `null` or `undefined`. This is useful because `@ViewChild()` properties are initially `undefined` when the component instance is created and are only set later by Angular once the view initialization is completed.

The reference to `NgForm` that is acquired through `@ViewChild('f')` provides access to form properties and methods from within your component class, giving you programmatic control over the form. For example, you can do the following:

- Access form values (`this.signupForm.value`).
- Check validity (`this.signupForm.valid`).
- Set default values programmatically.
- Trigger validation checks.
- Manipulate form controls programmatically.

Here's a simple example:

```typescript
import { Component, ViewChild } from '@angular/core';
import { NgForm } from '@angular/forms';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-sign-up',
  template: `
    <form (ngSubmit)="onSubmit()" #f="ngForm">
      <!-- form fields -->
    </form>
  `
})
export class SignUpComponent {
  @ViewChild('f') signupForm!: NgForm;

  onSubmit() {
    if (this.signupForm.valid) {
      // Perform the submission logic
    }
  }
}
```

`@ViewChild()` also accepts a configuration object where you can specify whether you want to access the element when the view is first checked (`{ static: true }`) or after change detection has run (`{ static: false }`).

Keep in mind that `@ViewChild()` only becomes populated after the view initialization lifecycle hook `ngAfterViewInit()` has run, meaning you will not be able to access it in earlier lifecycle hooks like `ngOnInit()`.

